[EU's bluetongue map, presenting the status of the territories in member countries in regard to the presence of BT virus strains, last updated on 5 Oct 2021, is available at https://ec.europa.eu/food/system/files/2021-10/ad_control-measures_bt_restrictedzones-map.pdf. The southern half of Portugal, south-west Spain (Andalusia and the southern part of Extremadura, bordering Portugal) and the Balearic islands, are indicated as infected by BTV-4. - Mod.AS]

******
[3] Tunisia, sheep.
Date: Tue 12 Oct 2021
Source: Tunisian Ministry of Agriculture [in Arabic, trans. Mod.SF, abridged, edited]
http://www.agriculture.tn/?p=20649


As part of the monitoring of the bluetongue [BT] situation and in view of the climatic factors that our country has witnessed, such as high temperatures and high humidity suitable for the reproduction of insects, especially vectors of diseases such as BT disease in sheep and cattle, the Ministry of Agriculture, based on reports issued by regional veterinary services and the results of the laboratory analyses carried out at the Veterinary Research Institute in Tunis, reports that 33 BT outbreaks have been recorded in cattle and sheep in some governorates to date [12 Oct 2021].

The health situation is considered stable in our country compared to the previous year [2020] (160 outbreaks), but it requires caution and close follow-up.

The Ministry of Agriculture states that BT disease isn't a zoonotic disease. It has been an endemic disease in our country since 1999 and is present in most countries north and south of the Mediterranean Basin and in African countries. This disease is transmitted to animals through biting insects (_Culicoides_) that breed in the presence of certain climatic factors such as humidity and high temperatures.

