[Dr Mahmoud Orabi is gratefully acknowledged for his submissions.

The following information, addressing BTV and its vectors in Tunisia, is extracted/edited from a 2017 paper [Ref 1].

"Since 1999, BTV outbreaks have occurred in Tunisia, caused by 4 serotypes, BTV2, BTV1, BTV4 and BTV3, respectively during the years 2000, 2006, 2009, and 2016. Epizootic haemorrhagic disease (EHD, similarly a culicoides-borne orbivirus, affecting cattle) was detected for the 1st time in Tunisia and in other Northern African countries in 2006. These incursions have caused considerable economic losses. Our study had the goal to describe diversity, distribution, and seasonal dynamics of Culicoides. A total of 11 582 Culicoides specimens were collected from 336 light traps, comprising 25 species, of which 7 were identified for the 1st time in Tunisia, increasing to 35 the total number of Culicoides species now reported in this country. Both BTV1 and BTV4 were detected in _C. imicola_".

References
1. Sghaier S, Hammami S, Goffredo M et al. New species of the genus Culicoides (Diptera Ceratopogonidae) for Tunisia, with detection of Bluetongue viruses in vectors. Vet Ital. 2017 Dec 29;53(4):357-366. https://doi.org/10.12834/VetIt.986.5216.2.

The above study (see fig. 5) found that the population dynamics of _C. imicola_ shows a peak in the months of August and October. The vector's activity season is traditionally considered to span between June to November. - Mods.AS, SF]
